   "source": [
    "# Spam Email Classifier using Tree-Based Methods\n",
    "\n",
    "**Course:** MATH 373 — Intro to Machine Learning  \n",
    "**Topic:** Decision Trees, Bagging, Random Forests & Naive Bayes  \n",
    "**Author:** Plinio Durango\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Overview\n",
    "\n",
    "In this notebook, we build and evaluate a **spam email classifier** using multiple machine learning models. We progressively improve our approach using:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Decision Tree** — a single, interpretable classifier\n",
    "2. **Bagging** — an ensemble that reduces variance by averaging many trees\n",
    "3. **Random Forest** — bagging with additional feature randomness to decorrelate trees\n",
    "4. **Naive Bayes** — a probabilistic baseline well-suited for text classification\n",
    "\n",
    "We follow a consistent pipeline: **load → preprocess → vectorize → train → tune → evaluate → compare**.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why Tree-Based Methods?\n",
    "Decision trees split data based on the most informative features at each node, making them naturally interpretable. However, a single tree often overfits. Ensemble methods (Bagging, Random Forest) address this by combining many trees, trading some interpretability for much better generalization."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-s0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 0. Imports & Setup\n",
    "\n",
    "We begin by importing all required libraries:\n",
    "- **`os` / `email`** — for reading `.eml` email files from the file system\n",
    "- **`pandas`** — for creating and manipulating our data as a DataFrame\n",
    "- **`numpy`** — for numerical operations\n",
    "- **`sklearn`** — for machine learning models, vectorization, and evaluation\n",
    "- **`matplotlib`** — for visualizing feature importances and results\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Note:** Run `pip install scikit-learn pandas matplotlib numpy` if any package is missing."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-imports",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import os\n",
    "import email\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier\n",
    "from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingClassifier, RandomForestClassifier\n",
    "from sklearn.naive_bayes import MultinomialNB\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, cross_val_score, GridSearchCV\n",
    "from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-s1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 1. Data Loading\n",
    "\n",
    "Our dataset consists of real `.eml` files — raw email messages in standard Internet Message Format (RFC 2822).\n",
    "\n",
    "### The `parse_eml_folder` function\n",
    "This function:\n",
    "1. Iterates over all `.eml` files in a folder (sorted for reproducibility)\n",
    "2. Opens each file with `errors='ignore'` to handle encoding issues gracefully\n",
    "3. Extracts the body — handling both **multipart** emails (which have attachments/HTML/text parts) and **simple single-part** emails\n",
    "4. Returns a **pandas DataFrame** with one row per email\n",
    "\n",
    "### Labeling\n",
    "The `X-Spam-Status` header contains the spam flag set by the mail server.\n",
    "- **1** = spam (header starts with 'Yes')\n",
    "- **0** = ham (legitimate email)\n",
    "\n",
    "We apply this directly to both train and test sets to create our target variable `label`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-load",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def parse_eml_folder(folder_path):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Parse all .eml files in a folder into a pandas DataFrame.\"\"\"\n",
    "    records = []\n",
    "    for filename in sorted(os.listdir(folder_path)):\n",
    "        if not filename.endswith('.eml'):\n",
    "            continue\n",
    "        with open(os.path.join(folder_path, filename), 'r', errors='ignore') as f:\n",
    "            msg = email.message_from_file(f)\n",
    "\n",
    "        body = ''\n",
    "        if msg.is_multipart():\n",
    "            for part in msg.walk():\n",
    "                if part.get_content_type() == 'text/plain':\n",
    "                    body = part.get_payload(decode=True).decode(errors='ignore')\n",
    "                    break\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            body = msg.get_payload(decode=True).decode(errors='ignore')\n",
    "\n",
    "        records.append({\n",
    "            'filename':    filename,\n",
    "            'subject':     msg.get('Subject', ''),\n",
    "            'sender':      msg.get('From', ''),\n",
    "            'body':        body,\n",
    "            'spam_status': msg.get('X-Spam-Status', '')\n",
    "        })\n",
    "    return pd.DataFrame(records)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Update these paths to point to your dataset location\n",
    "train_df = parse_eml_folder(os.path.expanduser('~/Downloads/TRAINING'))\n",
    "test_df  = parse_eml_folder(os.path.expanduser('~/Downloads/TESTING'))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create binary label: 1 = spam, 0 = ham\n",
    "train_df['label'] = train_df['spam_status'].str.startswith('Yes').astype(int)\n",
    "test_df['label']  = test_df['spam_status'].str.startswith('Yes').astype(int)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(train_df.shape, test_df.shape)\n",
    "train_df.head()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-s2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 2. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)\n",
    "\n",
    "Before building any model, we always explore the data to understand its structure.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key things to check:\n",
    "- **Shape** — how many rows and columns do we have?\n",
    "- **Missing values** — are there null values that need handling?\n",
    "- **Class distribution** — is the dataset balanced between spam and ham?\n",
    "\n",
    "### Class Imbalance Warning ⚠️\n",
    "Spam datasets are often **highly imbalanced**. This matters because:\n",
    "- A naive model that *always* predicts ham would still achieve very high accuracy\n",
    "- We must look at **precision, recall, and F1-score**, not just accuracy alone\n",
    "- **Precision (spam)**: Of emails we flagged as spam, how many truly were spam?\n",
    "- **Recall (spam)**: Of all actual spam emails, how many did we correctly detect?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-eda1",
   "metadata": {},
