   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 3. Feature Engineering — Creating the `text` Field\n",
    "\n",
    "Machine learning models need **numerical features**, but email data is text. Our first step is to combine the most informative text columns into a single `text` column for vectorization.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why combine subject + body?\n",
    "- The **subject line** often contains the strongest spam signals ('FREE MONEY', 'URGENT', 'Click here')\n",
    "- The **body** provides richer context\n",
    "- Concatenating both gives the vectorizer the richest possible text signal\n",
    "\n",
    "The resulting `text` column will be transformed into numerical features using TF-IDF in the next step."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-feat",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "train_df['text'] = train_df['subject'] + ' ' + train_df['body']\n",
    "test_df['text']  = test_df['subject']  + ' ' + test_df['body']\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Sample combined text (first email, first 300 chars):\")\n",
    "print(train_df['text'].iloc[0][:300])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-s4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 4. Text Vectorization — TF-IDF\n",
    "\n",
    "### What is TF-IDF?\n",
    "**TF-IDF** (Term Frequency–Inverse Document Frequency) converts raw text into a numerical matrix:\n",
    "- **TF (Term Frequency):** How often does a word appear in *this* email?\n",
    "- **IDF (Inverse Document Frequency):** How rare is this word across *all* emails? Rare words get higher weight.\n",
    "\n",
    "Words that are frequent in a specific email but rare overall get high TF-IDF scores — these are the most discriminating features.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Parameters Used\n",
    "- `stop_words='english'` — removes common words ('the', 'is', 'at') with no spam signal\n",
    "- `max_features=5000` — keeps only the top 5,000 words to control dimensionality\n",
    "\n",
    "### Critical Rule: Fit on train, transform test\n",
    "We `fit_transform` on the **training set only** (learning the vocabulary and IDF weights), then `transform` the test set using those learned weights. This prevents **data leakage** — the test set must remain completely unseen during training.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Note for Naive Bayes:** `MultinomialNB` requires non-negative feature values. TF-IDF scores are always ≥ 0, so our vectorizer output is fully compatible."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-tfidf",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(stop_words='english', max_features=5000)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fit on training data ONLY, then transform both\n",
    "X_train_tfidf = vectorizer.fit_transform(train_df['text'])\n",
    "X_test_tfidf  = vectorizer.transform(test_df['text'])\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Training matrix shape: {X_train_tfidf.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Test matrix shape:     {X_test_tfidf.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Each email is a vector of {X_train_tfidf.shape[1]} TF-IDF features.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-s5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 5. Prepare Labels\n",
    "\n",
    "We extract the target variable (`y`) directly from the DataFrames we created in Step 1.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Bug Fix Note:** The original notebook attempted to load labels from a separate CSV file and reassign them, which caused a `ValueError: Number of labels=3028 does not match number of samples=5`. The correct approach is to derive labels **directly from the parsed DataFrame** using the `spam_status` column — which we already did in Step 1. This guarantees the labels always align with the feature matrix."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-labels",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Extract labels directly from DataFrames\n",
    "y_train = train_df['label'].values\n",
    "y_test  = test_df['label'].values\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"y_train shape: {y_train.shape}, spam count: {y_train.sum()}\")\n",
    "print(f\"y_test  shape: {y_test.shape},  spam count: {y_test.sum()}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-s6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 6. Decision Tree Classifier (Baseline)\n",
    "\n",
    "### What is a Decision Tree?\n",
    "A Decision Tree is a flowchart-like model that splits data at each node based on the feature that best separates the classes:\n",
    "1. Finds the word and threshold that best splits the data (minimizing Gini impurity)\n",
    "2. Recursively splits each resulting subset\n",
    "3. Stops when a stopping criterion is met (max depth, min samples, etc.)\n",
    "\n",
    "### Strengths & Weaknesses\n",
    "| Pros | Cons |\n",
    "|------|------|\n",
    "| Highly interpretable | Prone to overfitting |\n",
    "| No feature scaling needed | High variance |\n",
    "| Fast to train | Sensitive to small data changes |\n",
    "\n",
    "### Cross-Validation\n",
    "We use **5-fold cross-validation** for a reliable performance estimate. The training data is split into 5 equal parts; the model trains on 4 parts and validates on the 5th, rotating through all combinations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-dt1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dt_clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)\n",
    "dt_clf.fit(X_train_tfidf, y_train)\n",
    "y_pred_dt = dt_clf.predict(X_test_tfidf)\n",
    "\n",
    "print('=== Decision Tree (Baseline) ===')\n",
    "print(f'Test Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_dt):.4f}')\n",
    "print('\\nClassification Report:')\n",
    "print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_dt))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-dt-cv",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "cv_scores = cross_val_score(dt_clf, X_train_tfidf, y_train, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')\n",
    "print(f'Cross-validation scores: {cv_scores}')\n",
    "print(f'Mean accuracy:           {cv_scores.mean():.4f}')\n",
    "print(f'Standard deviation:      {cv_scores.std():.4f}')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-s7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 7. Hyperparameter Tuning — Decision Tree\n",
    "\n",
    "A default Decision Tree often overfits because it grows until every leaf is pure. **Hyperparameter tuning** limits tree complexity.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key Hyperparameters\n",
    "| Parameter | Effect |\n",
    "|-----------|--------|\n",
    "| `max_depth` | Maximum depth of the tree. Deeper = more complex = more overfit risk |\n",
    "| `min_samples_split` | Minimum samples required to split a node. Higher = simpler tree |\n",
    "| `min_samples_leaf` | Minimum samples required at a leaf node. Higher = smoother boundaries |\n",
    "\n",
    "### GridSearchCV\n",
    "Grid Search exhaustively tries **all combinations** of the specified parameter values. Combined with 5-fold cross-validation, it finds the combination that maximizes generalization accuracy without seeing the test set.\n",
    "\n",
    "`n_jobs=-1` uses all available CPU cores to speed up the search."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-gs",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "param_grid = {\n",
    "    'max_depth':         [3, 5, 10, 20, None],\n",
    "    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],\n",
    "    'min_samples_leaf':  [1, 2, 4]\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "grid_search = GridSearchCV(\n",
    "    DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42),\n",
    "    param_grid,\n",
    "    cv=5,\n",
    "    scoring='accuracy',\n",
    "    n_jobs=-1\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "grid_search.fit(X_train_tfidf, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f'Best parameters: {grid_search.best_params_}')\n",
    "print(f'Best CV accuracy: {grid_search.best_score_:.4f}')\n",
    "\n",
    "best_dt = grid_search.best_estimator_\n",
    "y_pred_dt_tuned = best_dt.predict(X_test_tfidf)\n",
    "\n",
    "print('\\n=== Tuned Decision Tree ===')\n",
    "print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_dt_tuned))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-s8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 8. Bagging Classifier\n",
    "\n",
    "### What is Bagging?\n",
    "**Bagging** (Bootstrap AGGregatING) trains multiple models on different bootstrap samples of the training data, then averages their predictions.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Bootstrap sampling:** Each tree is trained on a random sample *with replacement*. About 63% of the original data is used per tree; the remaining 37% (out-of-bag) can be used for internal validation.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why does Bagging reduce variance?\n",
    "- Individual trees are **high-variance** — they memorize their training data\n",
    "- Trees trained on different bootstrap samples make **different errors**\n",
    "- Averaging uncorrelated errors reduces overall variance (while bias stays the same)\n",
    "- This is the classic **Bias-Variance Tradeoff** in action\n",
    "\n",
    "### Parameters\n",
    "- `n_estimators=100` — 100 trees; more trees → more stable predictions but slower training\n",
    "- `n_jobs=-1` — parallel training using all CPU cores"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-bag",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "bagging = BaggingClassifier(\n",
    "    estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier(),\n",
    "    n_estimators=100,\n",
    "    random_state=42,\n",
    "    n_jobs=-1\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "bagging.fit(X_train_tfidf, y_train)\n",
    "y_pred_bag = bagging.predict(X_test_tfidf)\n",
    "\n",
    "print('=== Bagging Classifier ===')\n",
    "print(f'Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_bag):.4f}')\n",
    "print('\\nClassification Report:')\n",
    "print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_bag))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-bag-fi",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Feature importances averaged across all trees in the Bagging ensemble\n",
    "importances_bag = np.mean([\n",
    "    tree.feature_importances_\n",
    "    for tree in bagging.estimators_\n",
    "], axis=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()\n",
    "top_indices_bag = np.argsort(importances_bag)[::-1][:20]\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))\n",
    "plt.bar(range(20), importances_bag[top_indices_bag])\n",
    "plt.xticks(range(20), feature_names[top_indices_bag], rotation=45, ha='right')\n",
    "plt.title('Top 20 Most Important Words for Spam Detection (Bagging)')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Mean Feature Importance')\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-s9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 9. Random Forest Classifier\n",
    "\n",
    "### What is a Random Forest?\n",
    "**Random Forest** extends Bagging by adding a second layer of randomness: at each split, instead of choosing the best split from **all** features, it considers only a **random subset** of features.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why does feature randomness help?\n",
    "In standard Bagging, if one very strong feature exists (e.g., the word 'href'), most trees will use it early in their splits, making the trees **correlated** with each other. Averaging correlated trees doesn't reduce variance as much.\n",
    "\n",
    "By randomly limiting features at each split:\n",
    "- Strong predictors can't dominate every tree\n",
    "- Trees become **decorrelated** from each other\n",
    "- Averaging decorrelated trees reduces variance even more than standard Bagging\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key Parameters\n",
    "| Parameter | Description |\n",
    "|-----------|-------------|\n",
    "| `n_estimators` | Number of trees (more is generally better) |\n",
    "| `max_depth` | Maximum tree depth (None = grow until pure) |\n",
    "| `max_features` | Features considered per split: `'sqrt'` (√n) or `'log2'` |"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-rf",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42, n_jobs=-1)\n",
    "rf.fit(X_train_tfidf, y_train)\n",
    "y_pred_rf = rf.predict(X_test_tfidf)\n",
    "\n",
    "print('=== Random Forest (Baseline) ===')\n",
    "print(f'Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_rf):.4f}')\n",
    "print('\\nClassification Report:')\n",
    "print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_rf))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-rf-grid",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "param_grid_rf = {\n",
    "    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 200],\n",
    "    'max_depth':    [5, 10, 20, None],\n",
    "    'max_features': ['sqrt', 'log2']\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "grid_search_rf = GridSearchCV(\n",
    "    RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42),\n",
    "    param_grid_rf,\n",
    "    cv=5,\n",
    "    scoring='accuracy',\n",
    "    n_jobs=-1\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "grid_search_rf.fit(X_train_tfidf, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f'Best parameters: {grid_search_rf.best_params_}')\n",
    "print(f'Best CV accuracy: {grid_search_rf.best_score_:.4f}')\n",
    "\n",
    "best_rf = grid_search_rf.best_estimator_\n",
    "y_pred_rf_tuned = best_rf.predict(X_test_tfidf)\n",
    "\n",
    "print('\\n=== Tuned Random Forest ===')\n",
    "print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_rf_tuned))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-nb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 10. Naive Bayes Classifier\n",
    "\n",
    "### What is Naive Bayes?\n",
    "**Naive Bayes** is a probabilistic classifier based on **Bayes' Theorem**:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$P(\\text{spam} \\mid \\text{email}) = \\frac{P(\\text{email} \\mid \\text{spam}) \\cdot P(\\text{spam})}{P(\\text{email})}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "It calculates the probability that an email is spam *given* the words it contains, by learning how likely each word is to appear in spam vs. ham emails.\n",
    "\n",
    "### The \"Naive\" Assumption\n",
    "The **naive** part means we assume all words are **conditionally independent** given the class label — meaning the presence of the word 'free' doesn't affect the probability of seeing 'money' in the same email (once we know it's spam). While this assumption is almost never true in practice, it works surprisingly well for text classification.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why MultinomialNB for text?\n",
    "We use `MultinomialNB`, which is designed for **count-based or frequency-based features** (like TF-IDF scores). It models the distribution of word frequencies within each class.\n",
    "\n",
    "### The alpha (smoothing) parameter\n",
    "- `alpha` is the **Laplace smoothing** parameter — it prevents zero probabilities for words that never appear in training data\n",
    "- `alpha=1.0` is the standard Laplace smoothing\n",
    "- Smaller `alpha` → less smoothing, more sensitive to the training data\n",
    "- We tune it using `GridSearchCV` to find the optimal value\n",
    "\n",
    "### Naive Bayes vs. Tree-Based Models\n",
    "| | Naive Bayes | Decision Tree | Random Forest |\n",
    "|---|---|---|---|\n",
    "| **Type** | Probabilistic | Rule-based | Ensemble |\n",
    "| **Speed** | Very fast | Fast | Slow |\n",
    "| **Interpretability** | Medium | High | Low |\n",
    "| **Feature independence** | Assumed | Not assumed | Not assumed |\n",
    "| **Best for** | Text, sparse data | Mixed data | Most tasks |\n",
    "\n",
    "Naive Bayes is often used as a **strong baseline** for spam filtering precisely because it's fast, simple, and handles high-dimensional text data gracefully."
   ]
  },
