    "---\n",
    "## 11. Model Comparison\n",
    "\n",
    "### Mean Squared Prediction Error (MSPE)\n",
    "We compare all four models using **MSPE**:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\text{MSPE} = \\frac{1}{n} \\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \\hat{y}_i)^2$$\n",
    "\n",
    "For binary classification (0/1 labels), MSPE equals the proportion of incorrect predictions (1 − accuracy). A **lower MSPE** means better performance.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Expected Outcome (from theory)\n",
    "- **Random Forest** should outperform Bagging (decorrelated trees → lower variance)\n",
    "- **Bagging** should outperform a single Decision Tree (averaged trees → lower variance)\n",
    "- **Naive Bayes** may outperform tree-based models on text data because it's well-calibrated for high-dimensional, sparse feature spaces — or it may underperform if word independence is too strong an assumption\n",
    "- Single Decision Tree: most interpretable but typically highest error rate"
   ]
  },
