    "## 12. Conclusions\n",
    "\n",
    "### Summary of Results\n",
    "\n",
    "| Model | Accuracy | MSPE |\n",
    "|-------|----------|------|\n",
    "| Decision Tree (tuned) | ~96% | ~0.038 |\n",
    "| Bagging | ~97% | ~0.027 |\n",
    "| Random Forest (tuned) | ~97% | ~0.025 |\n",
    "| Naive Bayes (tuned) | ~97–99% | ~0.010–0.025 |\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key Takeaways\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. Ensemble methods outperform single trees.** Bagging and Random Forest consistently achieve lower MSPE than a single tuned Decision Tree, confirming the bias-variance tradeoff theory.\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. Naive Bayes is a strong text classifier.** Despite its simplicity and the naive independence assumption, Naive Bayes often performs competitively or even outperforms tree-based models on sparse TF-IDF data. This is because text data is naturally high-dimensional and sparse — conditions where Naive Bayes thrives.\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. Feature randomness in Random Forest helps.** By decorrelating trees, Random Forest achieves slightly better generalization than standard Bagging.\n",
    "\n",
    "**4. Class imbalance matters.** With very few spam emails, recall for spam is the critical metric — failing to catch a spam email has different consequences than a false positive.\n",
    "\n",
    "**5. Model selection depends on priorities:**\n",
    "- Choose **Naive Bayes** for speed and strong text performance\n",
    "- Choose **Random Forest** for best overall accuracy\n",
    "- Choose **Decision Tree** when you need to explain every prediction\n",
    "\n",
    "### Possible Improvements\n",
    "- Use `class_weight='balanced'` or SMOTE to handle class imbalance\n",
    "- Try bigrams/trigrams in TF-IDF to capture phrases like 'click here'\n",
    "- Explore `ComplementNB` (complement Naive Bayes) — often better than `MultinomialNB` for imbalanced text datasets\n",
    "- Add a confusion matrix visualization to better understand error types\n",
    "- Try `BernoulliNB` (binary word occurrence) vs `MultinomialNB` (word frequency)"
   ]
